Hey Podcasters!

When I attended a massive college with 25,000 students, I often
felt lonely despite being surrounded by so many people!

It wasn't until I started to get involved with different clubs
that I felt like a part of the school community! And the longer
I'm around the podcasting industry, I'm realizing it can be the
same way.

So today, we're going to look at ways you can find community in
this big industry. Let's get to it!

(
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/92uplpov79unhqo86g4azu0vvld33bw/25h2hoh2w8ml4ku3/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnV6enNwcm91dC5jb20vYmxvZy9iZXN0LXBvZGNhc3QtY29tbXVuaXRpZXM=
)‚Äã

******************************
12 Best Podcasting Communities
******************************

The podcasting world is full of incredible people, but the
journey can still feel isolating when you're editing and
recording as a one-person show.

That's when having a community can help! Podcast communities
break that isolation by bringing like-minded people together to
share resources, provide support, and motivate each other!

So whether you‚Äôre looking for advice on how to monetize your
podcast or have a question about podcasting tech, there is an
online community for you.

In this blog, we break down the top forums, communities, and
Facebook groups for podcasters, entrepreneurs, and listeners
alike!

-->Read Blog (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/92uplpov79unhqo86g4azu0vvld33bw/25h2hoh2w8ml4ku3/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnV6enNwcm91dC5jb20vYmxvZy9iZXN0LXBvZGNhc3QtY29tbXVuaXRpZXM=
)
Read Blog (
https://www.buzzsprout.com/blog/best-podcast-communities )

******************
üí°Industry Insights
******************

‚ÄãApple Podcasts Updates Coming in iOS18: (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/92uplpov79unhqo86g4azu0vvld33bw/qvh8h7hrp4keokbl/aHR0cHM6Ly85dG81bWFjLmNvbS8yMDI0LzA3LzI1L2hlcmVzLXdoYXRzLW5ldy1mb3ItYXBwbGUtcG9kY2FzdHMtaW4taW9zLTE4Lw==
) The newest version of Apple's operating system will be full of
updates for Apple Podcasts! You can expect to see chapter markers
in playback, the ability to share timestamped links, and linked
chapters in the episode description.

‚ÄãBuilding a Big Podcast with Tom Webster's New Book: (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/92uplpov79unhqo86g4azu0vvld33bw/g3hnh5h3wlqg60hr/aHR0cHM6Ly9wb2RjYXN0cy5hcHBsZS5jb20vdXMvcG9kY2FzdC9idXp6Y2FzdC9pZDE0NDYzMzY2NTc_aT0xMDAwNjYzNDI5NTAw
) This week, the Buzzcast team takes a snap look at Tom Webster's
latest release, "The Audience is Listening: A Little Guide to
Building a Big Podcast." Tom's new book promises to offer
practical strategies that will help sustain podcast growth!

‚Äã

*************************************
Question About Buzzsprout? Ask Megan!
*************************************

This week, we had a Fan Mail question about recording software:

"Hey I need help finding the best recording app so I can get a
crisper sound. Any suggestions?"
While recording software is a great tool, your sound quality will
most likely come from technique and the microphone you're using!

But, if you're still looking for a new recording software, we
recommend recording and editing in Audacity (

beginners.

Squadcast (

                                      February 1 priority deadline for Learning Analytics and Artificial Intelligence (Online) M.S.Ed.                                    





Priority Deadline Tomorrow:
                                      February 1, 2025                                    


                                      Dear Candace,

The priority deadline for Learning Analytics and Artificial Intelligence (Online) is approaching on February 1. Submitting your application by this date waives the application fee, maximizes your financial aid opportunities, and ensures priority consideration for admission.

column7: Candace, welcome to "Personas and User Research: Design Products and Services People Need and Want." Your Users Will Thank You!
column9:
Hi Candace,

Great design is more than aesthetics‚Äîit‚Äôs about solving real problems. Do you want to increase profits? Drive innovation? Even save lives? User-centered design will get you there.

So, where do you start? And how do you stay on track?

The simple answer: Personas. These research-backed representations of your users give you the clarity to create products, services, and experiences that truly work‚Äîfor your audience and your organization.

AI can‚Äôt do that‚Äîit can‚Äôt empathize or understand what makes us tick. But you can. Master personas and user research, and you'll prove AI can‚Äôt replace you. Instead, you‚Äôll increase your earning potential and open doors to new, fulfilling career opportunities.

In this course, you‚Äôll go back to basics, demystify personas, and learn how to build them from the ground up. You‚Äôll be guided by usability and UX expert William Hudson, whose application of personas has resulted in award-winning, user-friendly products. Here‚Äôs what you‚Äôll get:

- A deep dive into design personas‚Äîwhat they are, why they matter, and how to get your team to use them.
- The best user research methods to truly understand what your users need (not just what you, they, or anyone else says they do).
- A step-by-step guide to affinity diagramming so you can turn your raw research into real insights.
- The ultimate blueprint for research-backed personas‚Äîcomplete with top tips, best practices, and pitfalls to avoid.

But this course is more than theory. With the optional course project, you won‚Äôt just learn about personas‚Äîyou‚Äôll create them. Get hands-on experience, build confidence in key design techniques, and walk away with a portfolio-worthy project. Show potential employers you don‚Äôt just know user-centered design‚Äîyou practice it.

Don't have time to do all the project activities? That‚Äôs okay! You can use William‚Äôs sample solution at any point and pick up where he left off. However, you‚Äôll benefit most if you take on the activities individually and compare your results with ours and your fellow learners. You‚Äôll get the skills to take your career to the next level‚Äîand have more fun along the way!

You can start straight away with the first two lessons here:
https://www.interaction-design.org/courses/personas-user-research-design-products-people-need

In lesson 1, you‚Äôll dive into:

- What personas are, how they promote user-centered design, and why they shouldn‚Äôt be ignored.
- The benefits of a deep understanding of your users‚Äô needs.
- What confuses people the most about personas.
- User research fundamentals for personas.

You‚Äôll also have many opportunities to share your work and get feedback from your peers and instructors.

To help you pace yourself, we‚Äôll unlock one lesson per week according to this schedule:

--- Course schedule ---
Available now: Welcome and Introduction
Available now: Personas: Why They Work and What People Get Wrong
Aug 5th, 2025: User Research for Personas: How to Truly Understand Your Users
Aug 12th, 2025: Affinity Diagrams: How to Find Patterns That Shape Effective Personas
Aug 19th, 2025: How to Build Personas That Give Focus and Get Used
Aug 26th, 2025: Course Certificate, Final Networking, and Course Wrap-up

Personas are powerful‚Äîwhen used right. Learn how to create and apply them effectively to build products, services, and experiences people can‚Äôt live without. Let‚Äôs go!

https://www.interaction-design.org/courses/personas-user-research-design-products-people-need

PS: You‚Äôll get 3 free months for every friend/colleague you help learn design: 
https://www.interaction-design.org/members/get-free-membership

Very best regards,

William Hudson
Mads Soegaard
Rikke Friis Dam

But if a fight is unavoidable, it makes sense to prepare. This is what China has been doing since the first Trump administration, as our cover package describes. And that is one reason why China is winning. https://click.e.economist.com/?qs=8d6148af4134af6dbb3f2e513ec5ff9d28345026f3e4f68690ad4414b928db2d0bf34c823f2dbfe4fd5bce3ae24e6d4746e748274d0a7193 Our briefing begins the story seven years ago, when China’s rulers took stock of President Donald Trump, realised that a serious trade war was likely, and set about identifying and fixing their country’s vulnerabilities. They also studied America’s weak points, in case they ever needed to exploit them. This foresight is paying off. Fast forward to today, and America is reeling at the realisation that China could seriously hurt it by weaponising its dominance of rare earths, crucial ingredients in everything from cars to fighter jets. Its new rules not only restrict the export of rare earths, but also require foreign firms to seek a licence to export rare earths obtained using Chinese equipment, or magnets containing more than a trace of Chinese rare earths. https://click.e.economist.com/?qs=8d6148af4134af6dba6865f4679c9c5289c5a642a3d446fdf18a70a0af2598d957c7d99fb785964ab4fef19ca3f78e7582484849d941ed5c As our leader explains , Xi Jinping is trying to develop and enforce a new set of global trading norms on the ruins of the old liberal order. Roughly speaking: cross China, and it can paralyse your high-tech factories. Much could still go wrong for China. Unless used with care, its new tools of economic coercion could alienate its trading partners, and send them rushing to find ways to reduce their dependence on Chinese goods. But for now, China is showing that it cannot be pushed around, and that the people in the White House who dismiss its economy as “weak” have grievously underestimated it. China’s rivalry with America was one of several topics our editor-in-chief, Zanny Minton Beddoes, and Ed Carr, our deputy editor, covered in their Insider interview with Steve Bannon, one of the architects of the MAGA movement. The conversation also touched on whether America is at risk of civil war and the possibility of Donald Trump serving an unconstitutional third term. It makes for alarming, confounding and compelling viewing. ‚ö°Ô∏è Social Highlights:
Subqueries: The basics
Learning about subqueries goes along well with CTEs because almost every CTE can be written as a subquery and vice versa.
Subqueries are a query nested inside of another query. Technically you can have subqueries in subqueries in subqueries in subqueries‚Ä¶ and so on‚Ä¶ but don‚Äôt do this to your coworkers LOL! They can also be turned inside out and written as a CTE (I‚Äôll show you an example of this later!) which greatly increases readability and interpretability. I highly recommend using CTEs for multiple nested subqueries or really complicated/long subqueries for better code organization and readability.
Subqueries vs. CTEs
A few differences between subqueries and CTEs are that:
Subqueries cannot be reused throughout the query unlike CTEs. CTEs can be referred to multiple times within the same query, but subqueries cannot be reused.
You don‚Äôt have to name your subquery (although I recommend doing so with an alias) like you do a for CTE.
Subqueries can‚Äôt be written recursively like CTEs. If you‚Äôre not familiar with this, don‚Äôt worry, it‚Äôs not used much!
Subqueries are generally harder to interpret since a reader has to start on the inside of the query and work their way out to understand it. I highly recommend using CTEs for more complex queries because too many subqueries can greatly decrease readability and ease of maintenance.
Subqueries in the WHERE clause
A really common example of a subquery is using it in the WHERE clause of the outer query. You use the subquery for conditional logic by using an operator and then filtering the original dataset for that condition. Check out this example below with an aggregate function, min( ):
select *
from orders
where 
   order_date = 
     (select min(order_date) from orders) --this is the subquery

-- you can also use other operators here, not just =
Here, the query is being filtered for all orders that have the minimum order date, which is the condition. They can also be used to filter for a column (or a list) in the where clause like this:
select *
from orders
where 
   order_id IN 
     (select order_id from payments) --this subquery produces 1 column
Here we‚Äôre selecting all the order IDs in the payments table and then filtering the orders table for those orders. This gives us all the orders data for the orders that are in the payments table. Why would we use this instead of manually adding in the IDs we want to search for like this?
select *
from orders
where 
   order_id IN 
     ('7364', '3820', '9818',...)
Imagine you‚Äôre working with a HUGE dataset with thousands or millions of rows‚Ä¶ It wouldn‚Äôt be convenient to type in or even copy and paste that many IDs into a query. Plus, you could even explode your IDE (not literally) by trying process all those!
Adding in a manual list requires you to figure out which ones to add ahead of time instead of them being added in automatically. This adds in an extra manual step into your process.
Perhaps the most important reason is that we don‚Äôt want to hardcode in ID values unless it‚Äôs an ad hoc request that‚Äôs never going to be used again. It‚Äôs better to use a subquery here because the list will dynamically change and refresh every time you run the query. We love fresh data!
Subqueries are great for quick 1-liner queries to use conditional logic in the WHERE clause!
See y‚Äôall next week!
Jess Ramos üíï

Hey Candace,

On November 9, 1989, a single announcement changed the course of history.

At a routine press conference, an East German official, flustered and unprepared, casually mentioned that citizens would soon be allowed to cross the heavily fortified Berlin Wall. He didn‚Äôt specify when or how.

Confused but emboldened, thousands of East Berliners gathered at the wall that same evening, demanding to cross. The overwhelmed border guards, unsure of what to do, opened the gates.

By morning, the Berlin Wall ‚Äî a seemingly unbreakable symbol of division ‚Äî began to crumble, and with it, the Iron Curtain.

It‚Äôs easy to see the fall of the Berlin Wall as an inevitable historical moment, but what‚Äôs fascinating is that it wasn‚Äôt a grand master plan that started it. It was a small, seemingly inconsequential action ‚Äî a vague announcement ‚Äî that triggered the collapse of an entire regime.

This story is a striking example of what author Charles Duhigg calls the Power of Small Wins in his book The Power of Habit. Small actions create a ripple effect that can lead to monumental outcomes.

In psychology, this phenomenon is often referred to as behavioural momentum ‚Äî the idea that once we start something small, it‚Äôs easier to keep going. It‚Äôs the reason why writing just one sentence can turn into a full essay, or taking a 5-minute walk can lead to a 30-minute workout.

Interestingly, researchers at Stanford University found that small wins also reduce the psychological barriers to starting. When tasks feel overwhelming, our brains instinctively resist them. But when we focus on just the first, smallest step, we bypass that resistance.

The physicist Lorne Whitehead demonstrated this idea with dominos in a literal sense.

He showed that a single domino could knock over another domino 1.5 times its size, creating a chain reaction where tiny efforts lead to massive impact. By the 29th domino, you could theoretically topple a structure as tall as the Empire State Building.

This domino effect isn‚Äôt just about momentum ‚Äî it‚Äôs about unlocking exponential growth.

It‚Äôs why businesses focus on ‚Äúkeystone habits,‚Äù as Duhigg calls them. These are small changes, like exercising or journaling, that trigger larger, positive shifts in other areas of life.

It also ties into the broader concept of leverage, which Cal Newport explores in Deep Work. Some actions, no matter how small, have disproportionate effects. Identifying these high-leverage activities ‚Äî your dominos ‚Äî is one of the most powerful ways to create lasting change.

The Berlin Wall didn‚Äôt fall in one night. It began with small cracks, whispers of dissent, and tiny shifts in policy that eventually toppled the entire structure.

And the same is true for us. Big goals don‚Äôt demand superhuman effort or grand gestures. They start with a single step, a small win, a single domino.

And here‚Äôs the exciting part: we‚Äôre heading into the final month of 2024, which means there‚Äôs still plenty of time to set those dominos in motion for the year ahead. If one of your goals for 2025 is to start or grow a YouTube channel, why not give yourself a head start right now?

column9:
Hey friends,

Quick thing before we start: Over the past few months, my team
and I have been developing VoicePal, a ghostwriter app that helps
you turn rambling thoughts spoken-out-loud into written first
drafts. I‚Äôve mentioned it a few times in this newsletter, and
I‚Äôve had various replies asking how I actually use the app
myself, so I recorded a walkthrough of how I use Voicepal for
brainstorming ideas and creating a v1 of this very newsletter (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhn5n886c6h8lmg400cg/qvh8h8urlv43e4bg/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dj1DcDMxNDlfbjlDaw==
). Side-note: we‚Äôve released a bunch of cool updates in recent
weeks, including the ability to record 50+ languages, fresh draft
templates, and more. You can check it out on iOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhn5n886c6h8lmg400cg/8ghqh3ul7328w9il/aHR0cHM6Ly9hcHBzLmFwcGxlLmNvbS91cy9hcHAvdm9pY2VwYWwteW91ci1haS1naG9zdHdyaXRlci9pZDY0NzE1NTIwMDc=
) and Android (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhn5n886c6h8lmg400cg/dphehmu02koxd6hl/aHR0cHM6Ly9wbGF5Lmdvb2dsZS5jb20vc3RvcmUvYXBwcy9kZXRhaWxzP2lkPWNvbS5jaG9pY2VhcHBzLnJlY2lwZXNmZHc=
) ü•≥

Anyway, this week, I want to share some thoughts on finite and
infinite games. A few weeks ago, we hit 6 million subscribers on
YouTube. It‚Äôs a big milestone and me five years ago would be
delighted to be here. But to be honest I couldn‚Äôt help but have a
bit of an existential moment. even though we‚Äôve hit this massive
milestone, our views have actually dropped compared to last year
(maybe I‚Äôll write about this in an upcoming issue) which made me
question what I‚Äôm trying to do as a creator.

In these existential moments, I find it helpful to think about
the concept of ‚Äúfinite and infinite games‚Äù. This idea comes from
James P. Carse, who wrote about it in the 1980s. Carse writes
that there are two types of games in life:

* Finite games (where the goal is to win)
* Infinite games (where the goal is to keep playing).

Finite games have a clear endpoint and a measurable outcome
whereas infinite games don‚Äôt have an endpoint at all and no clear
sign of ‚Äúsuccess‚Äù. Here are some examples that come to mind as I
write this:

‚ñ∂Ô∏è YouTube

* Finite game: Get 1 million subscribers
* Infinite game: To keep teaching the stuff I‚Äôm interested in on
the internet

‚ù§Ô∏è Relationships

* Finite game: An incredible wedding where the guests are
absolutely blown away
* Infinite game: A loving and healthy marriage

üí™ Fitness

* Finite game: Getting six-pack abs
* Infinite game: Learning to enjoy exercise

üíª Career

* Finite game: Make enough money to retire by 40
* Infinite game: Find work that you‚Äôd continue doing even if you
weren‚Äôt paid

Whenever I‚Äôm feeling a bit down about work (which seems to happen
about every quarter for the past several years), I‚Äôve started
asking myself: ‚ÄúAm I feeling bad because I‚Äôm losing at a finite
game? Or is it because I‚Äôve lost sight of the infinite game I‚Äôm
trying to play?‚Äù

We‚Äôre all human - it‚Äôs ridiculously easy to get sucked into
playing finite games. They give us clear goals and that sweet
dopamine hit of achievement. But I‚Äôm starting to recognise that
true enjoyment comes from playing the infinite game, even if that
means sometimes sacrificing short-term wins for long-term
sustainability.

This doesn‚Äôt mean we should never play finite games (I still get
excited about business milestones like hitting a certain profit
target üòâ). It‚Äôs more about being conscious of which game we‚Äôre
playing at any given moment, and making sure we‚Äôre not
sacrificing the infinite game just to win at the finite one.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

Dear learner,

Our latest course, Governing AI Agents (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWFCSv6G9GFPVd_nyq8sHFmzW5LNP255DZr4KN3mxJ7j3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3nVW2QrJsR5ZQ7J7W3d_WQW1xW6SfW4HBb-846pqJyW1gk686168sc7W6NbVkj4mnxnvW5kTSmZ6j7ff6W5QgGX92zmPR_W57KNgF4G2J18W9f445h6wmMfJW2XFv675w2l0WW33BvWk17tbPDW1dvyft5bYFyRW5kdYB82G5QLRW5hpmqv5sqX9WW8dn8J25gZn9SW5t769N4vtnSYW2bz8jG56FH1JN4v3C0PJHMCYW52m9HS7X-qjqW973J-F2BC23yW7nYZG61M6D3tW96lG1F1VDMk1W8VCc5x6YVp4QW21MrW04zR-S7W27hWkX3KYrNjN1q0ptYD04MnV_W4l23Yt12NVCdRwb1QYzNdf2rLywF04 ) , built in collaboration with Databricks and taught by Amber Roberts, teaches you how to integrate data governance into every stage of your agent‚Äôs lifecycle, so your systems handle information safely, securely, and accurately.

As agents gain autonomy and access to sensitive data, governance ensures they operate within defined boundaries, protect private information, and remain observable in production.

Enroll for Free
(https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWFCSv6G9GFPVd_nyq8sHFmzW5LNP255DZr4KN3mxJ7j3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3nVW2QrJsR5ZQ7J7W3d_WQW1xW6SfW4HBb-846pqJyW1gk686168sc7W6NbVkj4mnxnvW5kTSmZ6j7ff6W5QgGX92zmPR_W57KNgF4G2J18W9f445h6wmMfJW2XFv675w2l0WW33BvWk17tbPDW1dvyft5bYFyRW5kdYB82G5QLRW5hpmqv5sqX9WW8dn8J25gZn9SW5t769N4vtnSYW2bz8jG56FH1JN4v3C0PJHMCYW52m9HS7X-qjqW973J-F2BC23yW7nYZG61M6D3tW96lG1F1VDMk1W8VCc5x6YVp4QW21MrW04zR-S7W27hWkX3KYrNjN1q0ptYD04MnV_W4l23Yt12NVCdRwb1QYzNdf2rLywF04 )

In this course, you‚Äôll learn to:

- Apply the four pillars of agent governance, lifecycle management, risk management, security, and observability, to build safer, production-ready systems.
- Use Databricks Unity Catalog to organize datasets, define permissions, and enforce least-privilege access across your agents.
- Govern an agent in practice by anonymizing sensitive HR data, masking personal information, and granting it only the access it needs.
- Add observability with MLflow to log, evaluate, and deploy agents with full traceability and auditability.

By the end, you‚Äôll know how to build governed agents that maintain data integrity, transparency, and control throughout their lifecycle.

column7: Data Leadership Done Right: Focusing on Work That Matters
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/data-leadership-done-right-focusing

When you first start out as a data engineer or data analyst‚Äîor one of the countless titles crafted to give data professionals a sense of belonging in tech‚Äîyour focus is often, well, tech. You spend countless hours learning SQL, Python, and the latest tools. Nights are dedicated to refining data models and how other companies build data pipelines and perform analyses.
But eventually, something shifts. A light bulb goes off. You start asking yourself: What‚Äôs the point?
You‚Äôve built dozens‚Äîmaybe even hundreds‚Äîof dashboards. You‚Äôve developed complex pipelines [ https://substack.com/redirect/d9688e43-ae27-4244-aa78-b9f6820aa8d7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] designed to make data accessible for analysts. But does anyone actually use them? What value is driven by my work?
As the unsettling thought creeps in, you might start questioning your purpose. I‚Äôm just completing tasks my manager assigns‚Äîisn‚Äôt that my job? Shouldn‚Äôt they be the one deciding what‚Äôs important?
Some people get stuck there, deferring entirely to their managers to set the agenda. But others feel compelled to dig deeper, asking a more meaningful question:
What work truly creates impact?
The difference between staying stuck and making progress is being a ‚Äúneedle mover.‚Äù If you simply complete tasks without understanding the value, you‚Äôll struggle to advance in your career or create meaningful change for your organization.
As a data leader, [ https://substack.com/redirect/441fa540-1cd8-46a9-a09c-c8bca9076ea1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] your responsibility is clear: identify and pursue projects that move the needle.
Quick Pause: As many of you know I have been writing a book over the past few months focused on data leadership. This is one of the few chapters I am releasing early. 
In this chapter, you‚Äôll not only find actionable insights and writing but also over 30 minutes of exclusive video content split into two in-depth videos. These videos are only available here‚Äîyou won‚Äôt find them on my YouTube or anywhere else.
If you‚Äôd like to support this newsletter and gain access to this exclusive content, consider becoming a paid member today. Your support means the world and helps me keep creating valuable resources for you.
Along with the exclusive content, the early part of this chapter will also include segments from the article Thinking Like An Owner [ https://substack.com/redirect/75c50558-6f5f-4377-ab45-655965b28adf?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. column7: How To Take Action (Even When You Don‚Äôt Feel Like It)
column9:
Hey friends,

Greetings from a very warm London - given the usual summer rain
in the UK, it‚Äôs quite a nice surprise that there‚Äôs a heatwave
when we‚Äôre back for a few weeks üòÖ

Anyway, if you subscribe to LifeNotes (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhn35dvdc6h83v7v00bgh3d27w/dphehmue79l0z6il/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXIvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj10aW1lcl8xMSZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cHJvZHVjdGl2ZW5vdGVz
) - my personal newsletter that I like to see as more of my
weekly journal - you‚Äôll know that I recently spoke about this
idea of "locking in" and keeping my head down, working from like
8am to 11pm all day everyday on the curriculum for our $1k
Challenge.

In that email, I was reflecting on the relative value of ‚Äòlocking
in‚Äô - something which I‚Äôve not really done for a while but having
that uninterrupted time was incredibly valuable in focusing my
attention on what mattered for the course. But despite how
effective these sessions were, the hardest part of each day was
always the first 10 minutes. Even though I might‚Äôve just had an
incredibly productive day hours earlier, overcoming that initial
hurdle to get back into the flow was always a battle.

There‚Äôs actually a simple graph in my book that illustrates this
really well - called the hump of inertia.

The whole idea is that whenever you‚Äôre starting something,
there‚Äôs always a hump to get over initially before things get
easier and you begin rolling downhill. And how much you enjoy the
thing affects the relative gradient of that hill.

But no matter how easy it is to roll downhill, there‚Äôs always a
hump at the start and it‚Äôs very hard to get rid of it completely
because we feel fear, discomfort, and resistance with pretty much
anything that forces us outside our comfort zone.

For example, for about 95% of my YouTube videos - even though
I‚Äôve been doing this whole thing for the last 8 years - I still
get this feeling where I‚Äôm like ‚Äúugh, I really don‚Äôt want to film
this video today.‚Äù

But I end up doing it anyway and eventually, I find myself having
a great time - I just had to get over that hump in the first
place (see this in real time with this video (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhn35dvdc6h83v7v00bgh3d27w/e0hph0u7n3809oi7/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS94bTJDZ09LU0UtVT9zaT1YQkZRQTI4Y1RiRDhTczRG
) üòÖ).

Some people might call that discipline and discipline‚Äôs usually
described as ‚Äúforcing‚Äù yourself to do something even though you
don‚Äôt feel like it, but I don‚Äôt like thinking about it like this.
Instead, I prefer to think of it as understanding that feelings
are just internal bodily sensations accompanied by a narrative,
and they don‚Äôt need to dictate your actions.

If you create a false bridge between your feelings and your
behaviour - if you go ‚ÄúI feel X, therefore I must do Y‚Äù - that‚Äôs
when you start living at the mercy of your emotions. And sure,
sometimes your feelings do point in the right direction. But
often, they‚Äôre fickle, they change, and they don‚Äôt always lead
you where you want to go.

So just because you don‚Äôt feel like doing something at the start,
doesn‚Äôt mean you shouldn‚Äôt do it anyway.

Just because you don‚Äôt feel like hitting the record button
doesn‚Äôt mean you shouldn‚Äôt film the video. Just because you don‚Äôt
feel like going to the gym doesn‚Äôt mean you shouldn‚Äôt go. And
just because you‚Äôre a bit frustrated because you didn‚Äôt get the
grade you wanted in your last exam, doesn‚Äôt mean you can‚Äôt put
your head down and study for the next one.

Every successful YouTuber, athlete, and student knows this -
sometimes you do the thing even when you don‚Äôt feel like doing
it. And an actionable way to make that initial hump easier to
overcome is to use the 5 Minute Rule which you might‚Äôve heard me
talk about before.

Essentially, set a timer for 5 minutes and commit to just getting
started - don‚Äôt think beyond those 5 minutes, just set the timer
and get started. Don‚Äôt put any expectations on the productive
session that you‚Äôre going to have once the 5 minutes is up or the
idea that you‚Äôre definitely going to get into flow, because you
might not.

But from my experience, I find that I blitz through the timer
without even realising it 90% of the time and I get over that
hump at the start and momentum quickly takes over from there.

And I realise you might be thinking this isn‚Äôt a particularly
sophisticated technique but when you know what you‚Äôre trying to
achieve and just need that nudge to get started, it‚Äôs genuinely
highly effective, (as I found in putting together the curriculum
over the past few weeks).

Anyway, that‚Äôs all for this week - check out my issue of
LifeNotes here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhn35dvdc6h83v7v00bgh3d27w/7qh7h2u942rov7b9/aHR0cHM6Ly9ja2FyY2hpdmUuY29tL2IvMzh1cGhraDJxdmU5ZGYzN3h4bDc1ZjQ3ZHpvbm5oN2g2eDQ1bA==
) if you missed it where I went deeper on this idea of ‚ÄòLocking
In‚Äô and if you want learn more about building systems around your
goals, showing up even when you don‚Äôt feel like it, and creating
routines to stay accountable, then you might want to check out
LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhn35dvdc6h83v7v00bgh3d27w/owhkhwuw8m2r3muq/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXRpbWVyXzExJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
) which gives you the foundations and the systems to transform
your productivity from the ground up.

Finally, before we go, if you‚Äôve read this far, I‚Äôd love to know
what you‚Äôd like to hear more about in ProductiveNotes and what
type of content you find the most valuable - hit reply and let me
know üôå

Have a great week üòä

Ali xx

column7: Why AI Job Loss Is Actually Job Liberation
column9:
View this post on the web at https://metatrends.substack.com/p/the-job-creation-paradox

My recent conversation with LinkedIn founder Reid Hoffman revealed a counterintuitive truth about AI‚Äôs impact on employment. Here are five reasons why the job apocalypse narrative gets it backwards...
1/ Yes, AI eliminates entry-level repetition, and that‚Äôs exactly the point. Current data shows entry-level job losses down 16% in AI-exposed fields. But this mirrors what Reid told us: ‚ÄúIf human beings are trying to do a job by following a script that an AI can follow better, that will happen.‚Äù
The question is: why are we clinging to work that reduces humans to algorithmic execution?
2/ The real transformation is humans evolving beyond entry-level constraints. We don‚Äôt need to ‚Äúupskill.‚Äù We need to evolve into doing work that actually matters. As I emphasized in our conversation:
‚ÄúThe career of the future is entrepreneurship. It is how you use these tools to create value in the world.‚Äù
Every person will become what Reid calls ‚Äúentrepreneurially thinking,‚Äù deploying AI agents as cognitive amplifiers rather than competing against them for routine tasks.
3/ Every tech revolution creates exponentially more jobs than it destroys. Reid‚Äôs insight captures this perfectly: ‚ÄúI think if you look at the industrial revolution, the net effect is always more job creation in the long run.‚Äù
For example, take India, where initial 20-25% drops in entry-level software jobs are pushing engineers toward entrepreneurship: exactly where the real opportunity lies.
4/ AI amplifies human cognitive potential rather than replacing it. Reid described his productivity transformation: what used to take hours now takes 10-15 minutes. That‚Äôs human augmentation at scale.
As recent studies have shown, students learning with AI are progressing five to ten times faster than traditional classroom settings. What we‚Äôre seeing isn‚Äôt replacement‚Ä¶ it‚Äôs the democratization of superhuman capability.
5/ Timeline thinking separates winners from victims. The challenge is the compressed timeline we‚Äôre experiencing. Job displacement is happening much faster than many people expected.
But smart thinkers operate in decades, not daily panic cycles. While others fear quarterly disruption, entrepreneurs are building the infrastructure that will employ millions in roles that don‚Äôt even exist today.
Bottom line: what we‚Äôre seeing is the last generation of humans constrained by entry-level work. The future belongs to those who understand AI as a creativity amplifier, not a job destroyer.
Stop preparing for yesterday‚Äôs careers. Start building tomorrow‚Äôs.
Until next time,
Peter
